Company Overview

kampani avalkana

Bengaluru Foods Pty Ltd

Bengaluru Foods Pty Ltd is the parent company established to own, operate and expand The Bengaluru Caf brand across Australia. We have registered trading names for Melbourne and Sydney, giving us a clear pathway to multi-city growth.

Our flagship outlet in Melbourne will debut as a vegetarian tiffin caf delivering the true flavours and nostalgia of Bengaluru.

Target Market & Location Strategy

Target Audience

A large and well-established South Indian diaspora in Melbourne, deeply familiar with traditional brands like Nandini and Bengaluru-style cuisine. Official census data shows 258,000+ India-born residents living in Victoria and 243,000+ India-born residents in Melbourne alone.

Beyond the diaspora, we aim to introduce Australians more broadly to Karnataka's authentic tiffin culturebringing a taste of Bengaluru that has never been experienced in Melbourne before.

Flagship Location

Our flagship site will be in a premium suburb with high South-Asian population density to ensure maximum visibility and accessibility. The location has been strategically selected to capture both the diaspora and food-curious Australians.

Unique Value Proposition

A 100% genuine Bengaluru experienceno fusion, no adaptation, no shortcuts. Just the pure, untampered soul of Bengaluru's tiffin culture, served exactly as it was meant to be.

Executive Summary

kryakri sra

Bridging the Authenticity Gap

While Melbourne has a handful of cafs attempting to serve Bengaluru-style food, they fall short of delivering the authentic experience. Many achieve less than 40% of the genuine taste and quality you'd find in Bengaluru. It's not easyand credit to them for tryingbut they're nowhere near perfection.

We exist to bridge that gap and present 100% authentic taste. That's our promise.

Market Gap & Operating Model

Authentic Bengaluru caf experience missing in Melbourne. While Tamil and North Indian cuisines thrive, the unique Bengaluru tiffin culturebenne dosas, chow chow bath, filter coffeeremains largely absent.

Operating Thu-Sun (30 service hours/week, 52 weeks/year) with a conservative floor scenario of 150 customers/week @ $40 average spend, a realistic target of 220 customers/week @ $40 average spend, and upside potential reaching 260 customers/week @ $50 average spend.

Three scenarios guide Year-1 planning: (1) Caf-only break-even requires approximately 185 customers/week or $7,400/week revenue, (2) With Year-1 Nandini Product Distribution (conservative ramp: $64k revenue, $22.5k gross profit), break-even improves to 169 customers/week or $6,800/week revenue, reducing required customer traffic by approximately 9%, and (3) The realistic scenario of 220 customers/week delivers strong profitability with diversified revenue streams.

Founder's Story

sthpakara kathe

I'm Rajath, and I grew up in Bengaluru eating at the places that define the city's soul. CTR's benne dosa dripping with butter. Vidyarthi Bhavan's legendary masala dosa with its perfect golden crunch. Veena Stores and Taaza Thindi for soft, pillowy idlis that melt in your mouth. By 2 Coffee's filter coffee so strong it could wake the dead. These weren't just restaurantsthey were rituals, traditions passed down through generations. Every bite carried decades of perfected technique, every sip told a story of uncompromising quality. That's the Bengaluru I know. That's the taste I carry in my DNA.

Then life whisked me away to Melbourne, and yet I felt an echo of something familiar pulling at me, but something deeper seemed to be missing on my plate. In a way, I realized that nostalgia was my secret ingredient.

So I started to chase that lost flavor. I transformed my kitchen into a laboratory of dosa trials. Midnight batter-stirring became my ritual. I bombarded my aunt and grandmother with phone calls, desperate for their secret tips. I learned the hard way how patience turns rice and lentils into golden, crisp magic. My friends teased that I had opened a dosa factory at home but it felt worth every burnt pancake.

The moment of truth came one Sunday morning when I served my homemade dosa to my skeptical housemates. Their eyes closed with the first bite, and I knew I'd done it. They insisted I share this with more people. That warmth, that pure taste of Bengaluru, was too good to keep to myself.

And so, The Bengaluru Caf Melbourne was born. Now every dosa that leaves our kitchen carries a little story of those laughter-filled mornings back home. It's a place where flavor feeds the soul, where every visitor finds a taste of Bengaluru in the heart of Melbourne.

"We simply want to serve Bengaluru on a plate in Melbourne, period."

Rajath Bangalore Harish

Vision

Build one of Australia's most admired South-Indian vegetarian caf brandsintroducing the warmth and flavours of Bengaluru to cities across the country. We aspire to expand beyond community dining and establish a culinary movement that resonates with all Australians.

Mission

Uncompromised heritage

Serve genuine Bengaluru recipes prepared with heirloom techniques and a focused menu to ensure every benne dosa, Thatte idli and tumbler of filter coffee tastes like it does back home.

Thoughtful experience

Operate ThursdaySunday for freshness and exclusivity, emphasising sustainable practices from sourcing to packaging.

Cultural storytelling

Create an atmosphere that evokes Old Bengaluru through music, dcor and service, giving guests a portal into Karnataka's tiffin culture.

Scalable integrity

Develop proprietary processes and training that allow us to grow without diluting quality, so that each new caf honours the original.

Sustainability & Ethics

susthirate mattu nti

"Good food tastes better when it's good for the planet."

Compostable Serveware

All plates, cups, and cutlery are 100% biodegradable areca leaf products part of our commitment to minimizing plastic usage. This also reduces labour costs by eliminating dishwashing.

Ethical Sourcing & Traceability

Through our partnership with Murundi Group (official Australian distributor of Nandini Dairy), we source key ingredients directly from trusted farms in Karnataka. Each ingredient's journeyfrom farm to kitchenis transparent via QR codes. Every bag of rice, lentils, ghee or coffee has a story, and we tell it.

Minimizing Plastic Usage

We are committed to significantly reducing plastic in our operations and packaging. Most elements of our servicefrom takeaway containers to cutleryuse sustainable alternatives wherever possible.

Food-Waste Reduction & Cost Discipline

Operating four days per week (ThursdaySunday) keeps waste to a minimum. Fresh ingredients, precise planning, no overproduction. COGS maintained at 22-28% through portion control, batch preparation, and vegetarian efficiency. Disposables add only $1.05-$1.20 per customer.

Vegetarian, Not Plant-Based

Our menu is 100% vegetarian, but we proudly use dairy products like Nandini ghee and butterauthentic to Bengaluru cuisine. We're not plant-based; we honor the traditional role of dairy in Karnataka's culinary heritage.

QR-Code Traceability System An Australian First

Our innovative QR-code traceability system lets customers scan and see the journey of their meal from soil to plate. This means each ingredient's origin (farmers, farming methods, transport, etc.) is transparent.

By ensuring full traceability, we champion food purity and build trust: diners know they're getting unadulterated, high-quality ingredients. This level of transparency is unprecedented for a South Indian caf in Australia.

From farm to your fork: Scan, learn, trust, enjoy.

Recipe Secrecy System

pkavidhna gaupyat vyavasthe

The Secret Mix System Engineering Consistency in the Kitchen

1

Pre-measured Packs

Exact ratios prepared in advance

2

Soak

Timed soaking for optimal texture

3

Grind

Consistent grinding process

4

Ferment

Temperature-controlled fermentation

5

Final Secret Mix

Secret blend added at the end

No Chef Dependency

The secret mix system ensures that no single chef holds the complete recipe. Each staff member handles specific stages, maintaining quality while protecting our intellectual property.

Consistent Quality

Pre-measured packs and standardized processes guarantee that every dosa, every day, tastes exactly like the last. Engineering precision meets culinary tradition.

Franchise & Multi-Branch Scalability

This systemized approach isn't just about protecting our recipesit's about building a scalable model for growth. When we expand to Clayton, Sydney, or even franchises, this secret mix system ensures every location delivers the same authentic Bengaluru taste without compromising quality or revealing proprietary formulas.

Operations & Staffing

krycarae mattu sibbadi

Lean Staffing Model with Award Rates

Streamlined team: 1 Head Chef + 1 All-rounder + minimal cleaner hours. All wages include weekend/evening penalty rates (125% Saturdays, 150% Sundays) and mandatory 12% superannuation. Disposable areca tableware reduces cleaning labour. Total monthly labour: ~$12,594( $142k/year)

Nandini Partnership and Distribution Rights

nandini pludrike mattu vitara hakkugau

Strategic Brand Collaboration

One of the most distinctive advantages of The Bengaluru Cafe Melbourne lies in our exclusive partnership with Murundi Group, the official Australian distributor of Nandini Dairy - the flagship dairy brand owned and operated by the Karnataka Milk Federation (KMF), Government of Karnataka, India.

Through this partnership, we have secured:

  • Exclusive distribution arrangement for Nandini products in Melbourne (via Murundi Group)
  • Direct B2B ghee supply to Indian stores, restaurants, and recurring monthly customers
  • Pre-order distribution model for Nandini sweets via community groups and events

Distribution Revenue Model (Year 1 Conservative Ramp)

Ghee Distribution:

  • Sell via caf counter, website, and B2B partnerships
  • Monthly commitments (bulk buyers + recurring customers)
  • Year-1 revenue: ~$32k
  • Target margin: ~40%

Sweets Pre-Order Cycle:

  • Orders close 15th of each month
  • Stock arrives ~20th, distributed immediately
  • 20-day shelf life prevents inventory holding
  • Year-1 revenue: ~$32k
  • Target margin: ~30%

Combined Distribution Impact (Year 1): Total ~$64k annual revenue with ~$22.5k gross profit (base case: 35% margin, range 30-40%). Year 1 is intentionally conservative to establish market presence and test demand. Volumes and revenue scale significantly in Year 2-3. This revenue stream is independent of caf foot traffic, reducing break-even from 185 to 169 customers/week. Distribution acts as a defensive moat and profit stabilizer.

Investment Structure: While the caf investment focuses on restaurant operations, the Nandini exclusivity creates significant competitive advantages and a secondary revenue stream that directly benefit investor returns through enhanced brand positioning, customer loyalty, and reduced financial risk.

1. Powerful Brand Recognition

Nandini is not just a dairy brand - it is an emotion for millions of Kannadigas. As a government-run cooperative and one of India's most trusted dairy names, Nandini stands for purity, authenticity, and nostalgia. By associating with Nandini, we instantly gain credibility and emotional resonance among the large South Indian diaspora in Australia.

2. Strategic Product Offering

We will feature Nandini Ghee in our cafe's kitchen and make it available for retail purchase at the counter. Ghee being a staple in Indian cooking and a core ingredient in our signature dosas creates a perfect cross-brand synergy - customers will taste Nandini before they see it on the shelf.

3. Exclusive Online Channel

As part of our rights, we will manage the exclusive online retail presence for Nandini products throughout Australia. This includes promoting bulk orders for Nandini Ghee and Nandini sweets during festive seasons, driving traffic to our cafe brand while opening an additional revenue stream.

4. Crowd-Pulling Advantage

Nandini's reputation as a Karnataka Government-backed brand acts as a natural magnet. Our cafe will proudly display "In association with Nandini (KMF)" branding, offering unique leverage in marketing campaigns, particularly among the Indian diaspora and students who recognize and trust the name immediately.

5. Long-Term Leverage

While our investor partnership covers only the cafe operations, the Nandini collaboration adds significant brand equity. It will help us attract foot traffic, enhance customer loyalty, and create cross-promotional opportunities. In the long term, this exclusive link positions us to potentially expand into a broader Nandini retail and distribution network across Australia.

Pre-Money

"We are not valuing this caf on Year 1 EBITDA. We are valuing it on exclusivity, first-mover advantage, and scalability. With Nandini distribution rights and no authentic competitors, AUD 200K secures 15% of a business positioned to be worth AUD 1.5M+ in 3 years."

Why This Valuation is Justified

1. First-Mover Advantage

There is no authentic Bengaluru-style restaurant in Melbourne. This concept is unique, capturing 100% market share of a defined category.

Investor Value: No competitors to split market, 40-60% lower customer acquisition costs, premium pricing power.

2. Exclusive Distribution Rights

Nandini dairy exclusivity creates a defensible supply chain moat that competitors cannot replicate.

Strategic Barrier: Competitors cannot source authentic Nandini ghee. Exclusive distributor agreements typically add 30-50% valuation premium.

3. Multi-Location Scalability

Melbourne flagship is proof of concept. Model replicable in Clayton, Sydney, Brisbane, Perth.

Chain Potential: Investors value multi-location upside. Trading names secured for Melbourne + Sydney = $1M+ revenue potential by Year 3.

4. Cultural Brand Equity

Bengaluru cuisine is underrepresented globally. We're selling nostalgia, pride, and identity not just food.

Emotional Resonance: Cultural brands command premium valuations. Din Tai Fung valued at $50M+ despite modest early EBITDA.

5. Premium Pricing Power

Customers are willing to pay premium prices for authenticity and exclusivity. Multi-item purchasing (dosa + coffee + pani puri + dessert) drives $30-$50 average spend, supporting higher margins.

Margin Advantage: Strong 67% contribution margin vs. 50-55% industry standard. AOV: $30-$50 vs. $12-16 generic Indian casual dining.

6. Comparable Valuations

Boutique ethnic cafs and niche hospitality startups routinely raise at 1-1.5M valuations despite modest Year 1 EBITDA.

Precedents: Guzman y Gomez ($1.3M, 1 location, 2006). Chatime Australia ($2M, 2 locations, 2009).

7. Scenario-Based Earnings Model

Valuation based on realistic scenario projections (~$72k EBITDA Year 1 with Nandini product distribution), not just caf-only. Conservative break-even at 169 customers/week (with Nandini product distribution) vs. 185 customers/week (caf only) demonstrates strong risk mitigation.

Business Model Strength: Caf operations ($458k realistic target) strengthened by parallel Nandini distribution activity ($64k revenue, $22.5k gross profit reduces caf break-even). Investors benefit from a more resilient business model with diversified operational cash flows.

8. Risk Mitigation Through Nandini Product Distribution

Break-even at just 169 customers/week with Nandini product distribution revenue (vs. 185 caf-only). Year 1 conservative ramp: $64k distribution revenue, $22.5k gross profit. Distribution provides defensive moat independent of foot traffic, reducing customer acquisition pressure by ~9%.

Downside Protection: Diversified revenue streams (caf + ghee + sweets distribution). Strong diaspora market reduces customer acquisition risk. Conservative path to profitability even at floor scenarios.

Why Invest Now?

Bengaluru Cuisine Has Proven Its Scalability and Cross-Market Appeal

Bengaluru cuisine has proven its scalability and cross-market appeal through multiple real-world success stories. Two recent examples demonstrate how authenticitywhen uncompromisedcreates explosive demand, rapid expansion, and category leadership.

Rameshwaram Caf (Bengaluru)

Case Study: Scaling Authenticity

Founded in 2011 with a single outlet in Bengaluru, Rameshwaram Caf grew into a dominant force in the South Indian caf segment by staying uncompromisingly authentic. What began as a local darshini-style eatery evolved into a multi-city brand across Bengaluru and Hyderabad, with ambitious expansion into Mumbai, Pune, Delhi, Gujarat, and Dubai.

Benne Cafe A Bengaluru Breakfast Phenomenon Outside Karnataka

Case Study: Demand Beyond Geography

Launched in May 2024 as a modest 12-seater caf in Bandra, Mumbai, Benne Cafe was founded by a Bengaluru-origin couple with a singular goal: recreate the true Bengaluru breakfast experience outside its home city. With a laser focus on benne dosa, idli, vada, akki rotti, and filter coffee, the caf positioned itself not as a "premium dosa brand," but as a neighbourhood Bengaluru darshinihonest, nostalgic, and deeply rooted.

Key Success Factor: Benne Cafe demonstrated that Bengaluru food does not need reinvention to succeed in new markets. By preserving taste, texture, portioning, and service style, the brand created long queues, cult-like following, celebrity patronage, and rapid expansionall powered by word-of-mouth alone. Its swift move from one outlet to multiple locations, with further metro expansion planned, reinforces the scalability of this model.

What These Case Studies Prove And Why The Bengaluru Caf Melbourne Will Work

Together, Rameshwaram Caf and Benne Cafe establish a clear, repeatable pattern:

  • Bengaluru food scales when authenticity is non-negotiable
  • Geography is not a barrierexecution is
  • Demand forms organically when nostalgia meets consistency
  • Breakfast-led, high-velocity formats generate exceptional unit economics

These success stories prove that Bengaluru cuisine, when served exactly as it should be, breaks borders. It has already conquered markets outside Karnataka and across North Indiacities with entirely different food cultures and expectations.

Melbourne is the next logical frontier.

With its strong Indian diaspora, multicultural food culture, caf-driven lifestyle, and appreciation for authenticity, Melbourne mirrors the same conditions that fueled success in Mumbai, Hyderabad, and Delhionly with higher spending power and lower saturation for true Bengaluru-style cafs.
